bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The National Education Association (NEA) is the largest professional organization and largest labor union in the United States, representing public school teachers and other support personnel, faculty and staffers at colleges and universities, retired educators, and college students preparing to become teachers. In 2010, the NEA had 3.2 million members and is located in Washington, D.C. The group holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code granted in 1906.

The NEA describes itself as a professional employee organization. The mission of the National Education Association is "to advocate for education professionals and to unite our members and the nation to fulfill the promise of public education to prepare every student to succeed in a diverse and interdependent world."

The NEA is a volunteer-based organization that relies upon its members to perform much of the Association's work. The members are supported by staff at the local, state, and national levels with the stated goal of "building great public schools for every student."

In 1857, Thomas W. Valentine, president of the New York State Teachers Association, issued a nation-wide invitation to teachers to unite in Philadelphia behind a common voice for America's growing public school system. After the meeting, the National Teachers Association (NTA) was formed with a membership of about 100. Minority educators were allowed to join at the start, but women were not allowed to join until 1866.

In 1870, the NTA merged with the American Normal School Association, the National Association of School Superintendents, and the Central College Association renaming itself the National Education Association. For the first 100 years of its existence, the NEA was controlled by administrators, and worked to further the interests of the "education profession" as a whole.
In the 1960's, after the first passage of a collective bargaining law for public employees, the NEA adopted union activities in addition to its operations as a professional association.
The NEA merged with the American Teachers Association (ATA), formerly the National Association of Teachers in Colored Schools (NATCS) in 1966.

In 1998, a proposed merger with the American Federation of Teachers (AFT) failed when it was rejected by NEA's Representative Assembly. Several NEA state affiliates have merged with their AFT counterparts, effectively forming a single association.

Over the years, the NEA has been a leader in national education reform and improvement movements. It has worked to improve the education provided to American school children through lobbying and campaigning on the local and national level as well as by promoting strong teacher education programs and continuous professional assessment and development.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection documents the commissions of the NEA. The collection contains nine series reflecting the bodies and their records. The nine series are: the Commission on Coordination of Research Agencies, Commission on Professional Rights and Responsibilities, Educational Policies Commission, Joint Commission on the Emergency in Education, National Citizens Commission for Public Schools, National Commission for the Defense of Democracy, National Commission on Teacher Education and Professional Standards, NEA Centennial Commission, and Legislative Commission.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The collection is organized into roughly alphabetical series based upon the NEA's organization. Records have been allocated largely to their offices of origin and reflect the work done within the offices, departments, divisions and units. Due to the immense size of the collection and the constraints placed upon the finding aid by the archival management system utilized by George Washington University, the collection was further divided up into parts.

Organized into 9 series: Commission on Coordination of Research Agencies; Commission on Professional Rights and Responsibilities; Educational Policies Commission; Joint Commission on the Emergency in Education; National Citizens Commission for Public Schools; National Commission for the Defense of Democracy; NEA Centennial Commission; National Commission on Teacher Education and Professional Standards; Legislative Commission.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research. Some files are restricted. Those files flagged as restricted are subject to review by Special Collections staff before being made available for research. As researchers request materials, a review of the documents will take place. Staff will remove any documents with social security numbers, employee numbers or other sensitive identifying information. Any document found including this information is closed for 90 years from date of creation, or until verifiable proof of a person's death is given. After these documents are removed the folder will be available for research. In some cases, items may be photocopied and redacted. The redacted copy will then be placed in the publicly available folder. All other materials in a folder will be freely available for immediate use and will be marked as having been reviewed by Special Collections staff. After folders have been reviewed using these procedures and the confidential materials have been removed, the restriction shall be lifted.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: In 1921, a Commission on Coordination of Research Agencies was created. The commission was founded to collect data and information on schools. The Research Division and commission worked together in early 1922 and devised a plan which would bring about a better sense of cooperation between the educational research agencies in the country.
As such the commission quickly disbanded and was enveloped into the Research Division.
"Addresses and Proceedings of the National Education Association of the United States Annual Meeting, Volume 60" by the National Education Association of the United States, 1922.
"The National Education Association and Educational Research", by J. Cayce Morrison, Review of Educational Research, 1956.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created within the Commission on Professional Rights and Responsibilities. The files include agenda books from meetings, conference information packets, investigation files, meeting minutes, reports and studies, and materials from the Workshop on Professional Rights and Responsibilities.

The investigation files are the highlight of these records and include notes, transcripts and details of the commission's investigations. The files cover a multitude of issues such as racism, desegregation, nepotism, breaches of contracts, and mishandled elections amongst others. These investigation files contain the source material for a final report which is often included within the files, or in the reports and studies section.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Commission on Professional Rights and Responsibilities was formed in 1962 as a combination of the National Commission for the Defense of Democracy in Education and the Committee on Tenure and Academic Freedom.

The Commission retained its focus on investigating the state of education throughout the U.S. including issues such as perceived Communist influences in the educational system, ethical dilemmas and charges including teachers, school systems and principals where help was requested in settling issues.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: Educational Policies Commission was founded in December 1935, by joint action of the NEA and Department of Superintendence. It sought through cooperative means to develop for American education long-term policies which will merit support for the profession and all citizens.
The commission sought to improve not only the theories about education but the also the conduct of education. It was made up of about 20 men and women and included the help of outside consultants.
In 1968, the commission was dissolved by a vote of 16 members of the National Education Association and the American Association of School Administrators.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created by the Educational Policies Commission. The files include materials from the civic education project and mental health project, correspondence, studies, manuscripts and publications, and meeting transcripts.

These records provide excellent insight into the priorities and areas of interest of the EPC. The combination of meeting transcripts and studies, manuscripts, and reports, show how issues were raised, addressed, and how the commission responded to advance their beliefs about the future of education in the post WWII era.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: In 1933, the NEA founded the Joint Commission on the Emergency in Education, to deal with the critical phases of the financial struggles facing education post-Depression. The joint commission advocated for causes such as federal aid to education, and financial equity reform in state and local support. The commission hosted a large national conference in August 1933, and released numerous reports, studies and papers.
In 1935, the economy showed signs of improvement, and combined with mixed results from commission actions, the joint commission was disbanded.
"Gender, Race, and the National Education Association: Professionalism and its Limitations" By Wayne J. Urban, 2000.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created by the Joint Commission on the Emergency in Education. The files include correspondence, minutes, newsletters, pamphlets and reports.

These records provide excellent insight into the management of schools and education in the post-Depression era. The large number of pamphlets and reports echo the need of the NEA to understand the concerns to education and help educate and organize a response to meet those new issues.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The National Citizens Commission for Public Schools was incorporated in May 1949, to help educate Americans about the importance of our public schools in promoting democracy and stressing the continued improvement of our educational system.

The group focused on creating local citizen's committees to work with local schools to solve problems. The Commission hosted several conferences and meetings and published sets of working guides for local groups.
In January 1956, the National Citizens Commission for Public Schools became a new organization and changed its name to the National Citizens Council for Public Schools.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: The Investigations files are subject to review by Special Collections staff before being made available for research. As researchers request materials, a review of the documents will take place. Staff will remove any documents with contact information or other sensitive identifying information. Any document found including this information is closed for 90 years from date of creation, or until verifiable proof of a person's death is given. After these documents are removed the folder will be available for research. In some cases, items may be photocopied and redacted. The redacted copy will then be placed in the publicly available folder. All other materials in a folder will be freely available for immediate use and will be marked as having been reviewed by Special Collections staff. After folders have been reviewed using these procedures and the confidential materials have been removed, the restriction shall be lifted.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The National Commission for the Defense of Democracy through Education was organized in 1941 by the NEA, largely at the behest of the Department of Classroom Teachers. The Commission was ordered to (1) bring to the public better understanding of the importance of education for all (2) Defend the cause of education against unjust attacks (3) investigate charges involving teachers, schools, educational methods and procedures; and (4) work for educational conditions essential for democracy.

The commission is also referred to as the Defense Commission throughout its history. The commission investigated the state of education throughout the U.S. and focused its powers on issues such as conscription, universal military training, perceived Communist influences in the Educational system, and charges including teachers, school systems and principals where help was requested.

In 1962, the National Commission for the Defense of Democracy through Education was renamed the Professional Rights and Responsibilities Commission to refocus on professional ethical issues and investigations.
"Education-Democracy's Best Defense" By Richard Barnes Kennan, Educational Leadership, May 1951.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created by the National Commission for the Defense of Democracy. The files include agenda books from meetings, brochures, investigation files, papers, materials of the postwar regional conferences, and workshop and conference reports.

The investigation files are the highlight of these records and include notes, transcripts and details of the commission's investigations. The files cover a multitude of issues such as racism, desegregation, nepotism, breaches of contracts, and mishandled elections amongst others. These investigation files contain the source material for a final report which is often included within the files, or in the reports and studies section.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Representative Assembly, at its 1946 meeting, established the National Commission on Teacher Education and Professional Standards (TEPS). The Commission was set out to develop a program of teacher recruitment, selection, training, certification and advancement of professional standards.

The Commission encouraged state affiliates to create agencies that mirror the goals of TEPS on a state level, held national conferences, and encouraged high school and college student organizations related to education and teaching.
The TEPS Commission continued until 1971, when reorganization combined four units into the Division of Instruction and Professional Development.
"The National Education Association: The Power Base for Education" by Allan M. West, 1980.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created by the NEA Centennial Commission. The files include articles, correspondence, agenda books, reports, skits, leaflets, letters and local newsletters.

The files reflect the planning, promotion and celebrations surrounding the NEA's Centennial. Public relations strategies and promotions are reflected largely in these records as some ideas came to fruition and others did not. The materials provide great insight into the promotion of the NEA during the 1950s.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The NEA Centennial Commission was formed in 1946, to assist in the planning of the NEA's centennial celebration in 1957.

The Commission made plans for the many celebrations throughout the national association and distributed information to local associations, the press, and throughout interested organizations. The commission also authorized films, books and articles for publication to the public in honor of the NEA.
The Commission disbanded in 1958, following the end of the centennial celebrations.
